<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-846-406  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 846 406.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 7 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Comdex Spring: WordPerfect holds back update. (release ofWordPerfect Office 3.0 delayed)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   WordPerfect Office 3.0 (Office automation software) (productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     Comdex-SpringConferences and MeetingsSoftware PublishersOffice Automation SoftwareProduct Delay.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COMDEX SPRING: WORDPERFECT HOLDS BACK UPDATE ATLANTA, GEORGIA, U.S.A., 1990JUNE 4 (NB) -- WordPerfect had planned to offer Version 3.0 of itsWordPerfect Office program at this Spring Comdex, but decided to hold backowing to delays in producing the documentation.andP;  The package was promised forlater this month, possibly in time for the PC Expo show in New York.andM;In addition, the company announced it will soon issue an update for itsDrawPerfect program, which first shipped last March.andP;  Version 1.1 features aruntime module for the distribution of on- screen slide shows, newpresentation advance options, a &quot;go to&quot; menu which can help direct viewers toother slides, and other drawing features.andP;  The update will ship in about aweek and will cost $15 for individual users who own version 1.0.andM;Responding to increased interest in Microsoft Windows since Version 3.0 wasreleased last month, WordPerfect announced it will develop a version of itsflagship word processor for Windows before it develops a version for thePresentation Manager.andP;  This is a reversal of its earlier position, and avictory for Microsoft over IBM.andP;  &quot;We saw the light,&quot; said spokesman JeffAcerson, &quot;and responded to our users.&quot; The company denied that delays indelivering Presentation Manager 2.0 were behind the decision.andM;Finally, Word Perfect demonstrated its new &quot;hold jockey&quot; feature on itscustomer support lines.andP;  A disk jockey has been hired to monitor thecompany's 200 support lines and tell people how many people are waiting inline ahead of them to ask questions, and how long they can expect to wait,depending on the nature of their query.andP;  Background music plays in thebackground, and the announcer also reads ads for upcoming versions ofWordPerfect products.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900604/Press Contact: Kathryn Pond-Sargent, WordPerfect,801-222-5004)</TEXT></DOC>